, and a standard Reese’s 2 Peanut Butter Cups bar in front. All the packaging is mainly bright orange with yellow and brown branding. Along the bottom, small white text explains the free-ticket offer: free tickets by mail with proofs of purchase from three bags or twelve candy bars, requests received by 8/1/02, six to eight weeks for delivery, up to six tickets per household, and details available at in-store displays. A yellow ticket slides into view on the right with large black text reading “FREE MOVIE TICKET,” visually connecting the candy purchase to the movie-ticket promotion.\n\nThe scene returns to the kitchen, where loose Reese’s Pieces and wrapped candies fly through the air in a stream. Orange, yellow, and brown pieces arc across the room, along with small wrapped candies. They move in a long, curving trail, passing in front of cabinets and the kitchen counter. E.T., the small brown alien character, is now visible in the kitchen. He has a wrinkled, leathery face, a long thin neck, large wide-set eyes, and a small body with narrow shoulders. He stands upright in the foreground, looking toward the flying candy with a calm, curious expression.\n\nThe candies continue to sail past E.T. in slow, graceful arcs. Some pass close to his face, and a few appear to drift toward his mouth. Behind him are wooden cabinets, a sink beneath a window with closed blinds, curtains, and countertop items such as a red bowl and kitchen utensils. E.T.’s head turns slightly as he watches the colorful pieces move around him. His large eyes follow the candies, and his mouth forms a small, pleased smile.\n\nA few candies hover directly in front of E.T.’s face, then one reaches his mouth. He appears to eat or taste it, his expression softening into satisfaction. He raises one long, thin finger beside his face. The fingertip begins to glow with a warm yellow-white light, standing out against the dark kitchen. Small Reese’s Pieces continue to drift behind and near him, their orange and 